All right, so about me. I have worked on some stuff.

20
00:01:04,076 --> 00:01:05,456
I always think these slides are kind of silly,

21
00:01:05,476 --> 00:01:08,058
because it is like, why you should listen to me on this subject?

22
00:01:08,738 --> 00:01:11,439
But basically, I have been in the video game industry for about nine years.

23
00:01:12,420 --> 00:01:15,901
Mostly working at AAA studios on stuff like Saints Row 2,

24
00:01:16,301 --> 00:01:19,203
Evolve, obviously, Bioshock Infinite, Red Faction Guerrilla.

25
00:01:19,943 --> 00:01:22,584
But I have also been in game accessibility for eight years,

26
00:01:23,064 --> 00:01:25,685
starting with AbleGamers, later becoming the chairperson

27
00:01:25,826 --> 00:01:27,806
of the IGDA Game Accessibility SIG,

28
00:01:28,627 --> 00:01:29,427
where I championed some.

29
00:01:29,747 --> 00:01:34,332
cool stuff, and then just last Monday there was the first ever

30
00:01:35,013 --> 00:01:40,158
game accessibility conference, hashtag GAConf, and I was the co-chair

31
00:01:40,398 --> 00:01:45,242
or co-director, whatever you want to call it, of that conference.

32
00:01:45,463 --> 00:01:49,747
I guess I've done work in this field, just trust me. I promise I'm not lying to you.

33
00:01:52,972 --> 00:01:55,632
So in this presentation, what are we going to be talking about today?

34
00:01:56,773 --> 00:02:01,054
So step one was how did we evaluate our accessibility after the fact?

35
00:02:02,035 --> 00:02:04,495
What did we eventually do to make our game more accessible?

36
00:02:05,116 --> 00:02:06,736
What did we learn during this process?

37
00:02:07,376 --> 00:02:11,618
And how can you just take what we did, use that knowledge to make your projects better,

38
00:02:12,098 --> 00:02:13,478
and not make the same mistakes we did?

39
00:02:15,182 --> 00:02:19,506
So obviously the first question was, how well did we do?

40
00:02:20,246 --> 00:02:22,728
And something interesting about asking that question is

41
00:02:22,768 --> 00:02:24,769
you have to have a benchmark to grade yourself against.

42
00:02:25,710 --> 00:02:27,191
And we didn't actually have one.

43
00:02:27,371 --> 00:02:29,433
So although there are plenty of guidelines out there on

44
00:02:29,493 --> 00:02:32,035
how you should develop an accessible game, there isn't

45
00:02:32,095 --> 00:02:34,697
really a scorecard to check your game against.

46
00:02:35,217 --> 00:02:36,258
So that's where we started.

47
00:02:36,358 --> 00:02:36,858
We made one.

48
00:02:39,228 --> 00:02:42,891
We took the guidelines that were published at GameAccessibilityGuidelines.com,

49
00:02:43,351 --> 00:02:46,173
the includification guidelines by AbleGamers,

50
00:02:46,653 --> 00:02:49,875
the special effect wish list, and then all of the recommendations

51
00:02:50,456 --> 00:02:52,357
by the IGDA Game Accessibility SIG,

52
00:02:52,817 --> 00:02:55,499
and we combined them into a giant feature list,

53
00:02:56,200 --> 00:02:58,041
of course moving duplicates because there were some,

54
00:02:58,902 --> 00:03:00,523
and kind of starting off that.

55
00:03:01,003 --> 00:03:05,867
In the end, we had about 150 unique accessibility action items

56
00:03:06,327 --> 00:03:08,308
that we could check against to see if we had done it or not.

57
00:03:10,738 --> 00:03:13,859
So once we basically had this giant list of features,

58
00:03:14,779 --> 00:03:16,699
we know not all features are created equal,

59
00:03:17,180 --> 00:03:19,700
so we evaluated each feature for a few different things.

60
00:03:19,760 --> 00:03:21,161
So number one was its reach,

61
00:03:21,621 --> 00:03:23,461
or the number of people it would benefit.

62
00:03:23,781 --> 00:03:25,182
The next one was the impact,

63
00:03:25,642 --> 00:03:27,782
so the difference it would make to the people it reached.

64
00:03:28,342 --> 00:03:29,563
And then the cost.

65
00:03:29,743 --> 00:03:30,963
Now when we considered the cost,

66
00:03:31,083 --> 00:03:33,804
we did that in the amount of effort

67
00:03:33,944 --> 00:03:34,704
that would have been needed.

68
00:03:35,204 --> 00:03:38,927
if we had done it originally, not what the cost of retrofitting it was, but if

69
00:03:38,947 --> 00:03:43,351
we had planned for it from the beginning, how hard would this to have been

70
00:03:43,371 --> 00:03:43,811
implemented?

71
00:03:45,204 --> 00:03:49,325
It was really convenient to get this list together and organize in that fashion.

72
00:03:49,745 --> 00:03:54,667
Because most of the lists, particularly the Game Accessibility Guidelines and Includification,

73
00:03:54,767 --> 00:03:58,008
are already bucketed in the same way.

74
00:03:58,989 --> 00:04:03,330
Based on this information, we placed each of the different features into a tier and

75
00:04:03,350 --> 00:04:05,491
we assigned it a point value.

76
00:04:05,591 --> 00:04:08,532
Something basic would be like subtitles.

77
00:04:08,592 --> 00:04:11,653
Just having subtitles, really basic feature, really easy to do.

78
00:04:12,534 --> 00:04:21,282
3 points, but having subtitles that have optional letterboxing, multiple size value, repositioning

79
00:04:21,362 --> 00:04:25,445
options, a lot more work but make the subtitles a lot better, 10 points.

80
00:04:25,565 --> 00:04:27,928
So it was kind of how much work did you put in for this?

81
00:04:30,109 --> 00:04:33,633
So we went through item by item and we awarded points for fully met goals.

82
00:04:34,762 --> 00:04:43,376
Partial goals for partial implementation or subpar implementations, like technically we meet this requirement, but it's not a good user experience.

83
00:04:44,197 --> 00:04:47,823
Zero points for just not having anything or marking it as not applicable.

84
00:04:48,434 --> 00:04:49,274
if it didn't work for us.

85
00:04:49,334 --> 00:04:53,976
So for example, if there was a guideline on how to do voice activation, we didn't have

86
00:04:54,016 --> 00:04:57,517
that, so we weren't going to ding us for not having something related to that.

87
00:04:58,417 --> 00:04:59,738
So what was our overall score?

88
00:04:59,758 --> 00:05:02,879
We ended up having like 64%.

89
00:05:03,579 --> 00:05:06,680
That's a D. Not exactly a great score.

90
00:05:07,281 --> 00:05:09,522
Some would say it's near failing, actually.

91
00:05:11,808 --> 00:05:14,449
So obviously we had a lot of room for improvement.

92
00:05:15,049 --> 00:05:17,770
So we needed to figure out where to start,

93
00:05:18,091 --> 00:05:20,011
and so we started going through the report card

94
00:05:20,131 --> 00:05:22,032
and looking for those basic items first

95
00:05:22,752 --> 00:05:24,953
to see where to start and what could be an easy win.

96
00:05:25,954 --> 00:05:30,097
And the key points were looking to see, like I said, if there were any of those basic features

97
00:05:30,137 --> 00:05:30,678
that were missed.

98
00:05:31,418 --> 00:05:34,541
And then we went through and started collecting player feedback.

99
00:05:34,941 --> 00:05:39,665
So one of the areas we really looked for was in our forums and seeing what players were

100
00:05:39,705 --> 00:05:43,469
already saying that they wanted and kind of cross-checking those two things to see if

101
00:05:43,489 --> 00:05:47,792
there was something that, oh, this would be easy and it's already something that players

102
00:05:47,852 --> 00:05:48,653
are requesting a lot.

103
00:05:49,775 --> 00:05:55,367
So, once we identified the list of features, we started scoping out the work and set our

104
00:05:55,387 --> 00:05:56,009
plan into motion.

105
00:05:59,630 --> 00:06:00,851
So what was the first thing we did?

106
00:06:01,751 --> 00:06:03,532
Actually, one of the most requested features

107
00:06:03,932 --> 00:06:06,033
for game accessibility was amazingly simple,

108
00:06:06,133 --> 00:06:07,493
and it had next to no cost.

109
00:06:08,074 --> 00:06:10,154
Gamers with disabilities often do not know

110
00:06:10,234 --> 00:06:12,815
if they can play a game until they buy it

111
00:06:12,936 --> 00:06:14,096
and bring it home, open it.

112
00:06:14,916 --> 00:06:17,117
And this is due to the lack of information

113
00:06:17,317 --> 00:06:20,198
about the accessibility features contained within the title.

114
00:06:21,580 --> 00:06:25,824
This information normally isn't made public, so again, it puts these gamers with disabilities

115
00:06:25,864 --> 00:06:29,227
in the situation that they've bought something that now they're stuck with because they can't

116
00:06:29,267 --> 00:06:29,687
return it.

117
00:06:30,207 --> 00:06:34,111
I guess you could trade it into GameStop for like $5, but that's not exactly a great value

118
00:06:34,151 --> 00:06:34,671
proposition.

119
00:06:36,092 --> 00:06:39,795
So all of the references, every list we looked at, just asked for this.

120
00:06:40,775 --> 00:06:43,017
So we grabbed the game accessibility icon,

121
00:06:43,477 --> 00:06:46,219
this little controller wheelchair guy,

122
00:06:47,119 --> 00:06:50,121
which is available from One Switch for just, you know,

123
00:06:50,481 --> 00:06:52,502
creative commons use, as long as you're denoting

124
00:06:52,963 --> 00:06:54,324
game accessibility information.

125
00:06:54,844 --> 00:06:56,925
And we made a simple online post,

126
00:06:57,065 --> 00:06:58,646
and we also posted this in our forums,

127
00:06:59,267 --> 00:07:01,008
that was just a factual list.

128
00:07:01,548 --> 00:07:06,259
We had to state what features we had, the options associated with those features, and

129
00:07:06,299 --> 00:07:09,006
we were honest about what our title didn't have.

130
00:07:10,311 --> 00:07:14,152
Pretty early on, we decided that we would rather be open about our game's features,

131
00:07:14,612 --> 00:07:17,753
and if we did not have something, be honest about it,

132
00:07:18,193 --> 00:07:19,853
and hope that in the future we could be better.

133
00:07:20,673 --> 00:07:24,114
Maybe even deter someone from buying our title in some cases,

134
00:07:24,374 --> 00:07:27,315
rather than having them buy it and go through that experience

135
00:07:27,335 --> 00:07:29,735
where they just spent their money on something they cannot use.

136
00:07:30,416 --> 00:07:32,136
I was talking to one of the co-founders, Phil,

137
00:07:32,636 --> 00:07:34,977
and kind of advocating on why we should do this.

138
00:07:34,997 --> 00:07:37,717
He was like, yes, we need to put that information out there.

139
00:07:38,177 --> 00:07:39,498
Not doing it would just be shitty.

140
00:07:40,418 --> 00:07:43,442
So it was very nice to get that kind of buy-in

141
00:07:43,462 --> 00:07:46,847
Because I don't know if you guys have ever been at a studio like that where you don't say

142
00:07:47,307 --> 00:07:50,632
You don't say anything that could stop someone from buying your title. So it was very

143
00:07:51,133 --> 00:07:54,096
refreshing to be someplace that that was honest and

144
00:07:54,998 --> 00:07:56,820
Didn't want to have a gamer buy something they couldn't use

145
00:07:59,854 --> 00:08:05,080
So, the next feature we actually got as one of the number one requested things out of

146
00:08:05,100 --> 00:08:10,267
the forums, and it also fell into the basic category on our list, was being colorblind

147
00:08:10,307 --> 00:08:10,547
friendly.

148
00:08:11,430 --> 00:08:19,195
So one of the things we quickly realized was we had a lot of UI elements that were using color only to identify the state of things.

149
00:08:20,156 --> 00:08:26,960
So one example was our ping system, which used red or green circles based on what you were pinging or marking.

150
00:08:27,860 --> 00:08:33,624
And the fix was really simple and it actually inspired us to make the ping system much more useful.

151
00:08:34,623 --> 00:08:39,465
So we ended up using a series of symbols to denote what wildlife was what.

152
00:08:39,865 --> 00:08:43,647
So you can see on the example on the left, the monster instead of a red circle now has a paw

153
00:08:43,667 --> 00:08:49,270
print icon. This plant that's going to eat you now has an exclamation mark. I don't know,

154
00:08:49,670 --> 00:08:52,491
I don't remember what I was pinging on the far right, but that was something friendly. So it

155
00:08:52,531 --> 00:08:58,034
just has the less scary paw print icon. So we were able to make things more recognizable and

156
00:08:58,054 --> 00:09:02,976
give people more information. And all of a sudden, you know, this section was now colorblind friendly.

157
00:09:05,560 --> 00:09:07,842
Something else that we noticed was in our game,

158
00:09:07,942 --> 00:09:10,485
if you were looking at player names,

159
00:09:10,886 --> 00:09:12,607
that was how you could identify what class

160
00:09:12,628 --> 00:09:15,891
someone was in if you just didn't know the characters.

161
00:09:16,191 --> 00:09:19,475
We realized that the names were just colors.

162
00:09:19,916 --> 00:09:21,998
So if you can't tell the difference between the colors,

163
00:09:22,679 --> 00:09:25,001
you don't know what class that person is in,

164
00:09:25,101 --> 00:09:26,883
unless you're super knowledgeable about the game.

165
00:09:27,647 --> 00:09:30,508
So with that one, we ended up doing something really simple.

166
00:09:30,548 --> 00:09:36,011
We ended up just placing all of the icons above the name.

167
00:09:36,091 --> 00:09:38,652
So that if you had colorblind mode turned on, these icons

168
00:09:38,672 --> 00:09:39,832
would appear and you could tell the difference.

169
00:09:42,013 --> 00:09:44,954
But we actually had some larger problems.

170
00:09:45,434 --> 00:09:47,755
Now I know the screenshot is probably a little blurry, but

171
00:09:47,795 --> 00:09:48,736
I liked it because it.

172
00:09:49,905 --> 00:09:51,186
showed one of our larger problems.

173
00:09:51,506 --> 00:09:53,247
We had several in-game visual effects

174
00:09:53,768 --> 00:09:56,990
that would either display the state on color,

175
00:09:57,030 --> 00:09:57,871
which was one problem,

176
00:09:58,251 --> 00:10:00,253
but it was compounded with this problem,

177
00:10:00,693 --> 00:10:01,754
and it was some visual effects

178
00:10:01,794 --> 00:10:03,575
were just getting lost in-game completely.

179
00:10:04,035 --> 00:10:05,957
So here, for someone who is red-green colorblind,

180
00:10:06,457 --> 00:10:09,759
this red icon in the green swamp would just get lost.

181
00:10:11,671 --> 00:10:16,493
We knew early on that adding a color filter was not the right answer.

182
00:10:16,553 --> 00:10:20,254
Colorblind issues, number one, only applied to certain visual effects,

183
00:10:20,695 --> 00:10:22,495
not everything, not the entire game.

184
00:10:23,176 --> 00:10:26,357
Furthermore, adding a colorblind filter could fix the problem,

185
00:10:26,837 --> 00:10:29,199
but it would also make the game really, really ugly,

186
00:10:29,779 --> 00:10:32,400
and it could potentially shift other colors that weren't a problem.

187
00:10:33,241 --> 00:10:37,167
into a problem state. So we knew that was not going to be what we wanted to do,

188
00:10:37,628 --> 00:10:41,154
but we still had to deal with this in some way. This was obviously still a problem.

189
00:10:43,418 --> 00:10:46,840
What we ended up doing was making an additional three version

190
00:10:46,960 --> 00:10:50,102
of that visual effects that the player would select

191
00:10:50,162 --> 00:10:52,244
before loading into the game.

192
00:10:53,925 --> 00:10:55,205
Let that sink in, that is right.

193
00:10:55,746 --> 00:10:58,908
For the features we found causing issues with color blindness,

194
00:10:59,348 --> 00:11:02,670
we ended up with four separate versions of that effect.

195
00:11:02,910 --> 00:11:05,792
The one we shipped with, and then three additional ones

196
00:11:06,092 --> 00:11:09,114
for the most common types of color blindness.

197
00:11:10,334 --> 00:11:15,576
Obviously, the cost of retrofitting colorblind mode for us was extraordinarily high.

198
00:11:15,676 --> 00:11:18,517
It literally quadrupled the work of some of the visual effects.

199
00:11:19,958 --> 00:11:25,740
But we knew this was something that we needed to be aware of going forward, and we kind

200
00:11:25,800 --> 00:11:30,922
of made it our internal goal to not introduce anything new because we were still releasing

201
00:11:31,122 --> 00:11:32,142
hunters, monsters.

202
00:11:32,462 --> 00:11:37,304
We didn't want to introduce a new character that would need to be hooked up into the system.

203
00:11:39,891 --> 00:11:45,193
In my screenshot here, I really like this screenshot because you can see that, like

204
00:11:45,213 --> 00:11:49,874
I said, when we turned on Colorblind Mode, it is not changing everything in-game.

205
00:11:49,894 --> 00:11:54,056
It is only changing these problem visual effects.

206
00:11:54,076 --> 00:11:59,038
The only thing that is different are the footprints on the left and the targeting reticule in

207
00:11:59,058 --> 00:11:59,398
the middle.

208
00:11:59,818 --> 00:12:00,818
This is really important.

209
00:12:00,838 --> 00:12:02,819
There are people who do Colorblind Mode wrong.

210
00:12:03,699 --> 00:12:04,440
all the time.

211
00:12:04,780 --> 00:12:06,580
So I really, it's like, just let this soak in,

212
00:12:07,001 --> 00:12:07,561
absorb it.

213
00:12:07,641 --> 00:12:09,462
If you learn something about colorblind mode today,

214
00:12:09,602 --> 00:12:11,142
it's that please don't do a filter,

215
00:12:11,663 --> 00:12:13,183
just address the problem areas.

216
00:12:15,164 --> 00:12:18,525
Now, like I said, we ended up being smart

217
00:12:19,246 --> 00:12:21,266
and basically starting at the concept phase.

218
00:12:22,138 --> 00:12:24,641
we would tell if a visual effect was gonna be a problem

219
00:12:24,661 --> 00:12:25,382
in colorblind mode.

220
00:12:25,862 --> 00:12:28,025
So if a gun had two different states,

221
00:12:28,125 --> 00:12:29,666
like charging and ready to fire,

222
00:12:30,287 --> 00:12:32,229
but the concept art looked like the picture on the left,

223
00:12:32,830 --> 00:12:34,371
we knew that wasn't gonna fly,

224
00:12:34,391 --> 00:12:36,254
and we'd just send that straight back.

225
00:12:37,794 --> 00:12:43,456
But if it had a other visual difference, something other than color, a second way of displaying

226
00:12:43,496 --> 00:12:50,438
that information, like the one on the right, we knew that that was going to work, that

227
00:12:50,478 --> 00:12:54,399
was good, we could use that one, and then we'd actually go about building the visual

228
00:12:54,439 --> 00:12:54,679
effect.

229
00:12:56,089 --> 00:12:59,250
In the end, we did have several additional updates to Colorblind Mode

230
00:12:59,430 --> 00:13:00,990
after the initial patch that contained it.

231
00:13:01,670 --> 00:13:03,591
We updated even more UI elements,

232
00:13:03,911 --> 00:13:06,331
and we caught things such as in-game outlines

233
00:13:07,072 --> 00:13:09,492
to make them also part of the system.

234
00:13:09,672 --> 00:13:12,473
The class icon fix that I mentioned previously,

235
00:13:12,493 --> 00:13:16,554
that ended up being so popular, we had non-Colorblind players

236
00:13:17,174 --> 00:13:19,875
using Colorblind Mode so that they could see that icon.

237
00:13:20,255 --> 00:13:22,935
In the end, we actually pulled that out of Colorblind Mode,

238
00:13:23,315 --> 00:13:25,516
made it its own toggle that was on by default.

239
00:13:26,577 --> 00:13:30,985
That just goes to show accessibility features will be used beyond your core player base

240
00:13:31,206 --> 00:13:33,189
and makes games better for everyone.

241
00:13:36,094 --> 00:13:38,719
The next one we decided to tackle was remappable controls.

242
00:13:39,787 --> 00:13:43,809
Although we had remappable keyboard controls on PC,

243
00:13:44,169 --> 00:13:45,649
we did not have anything for the controller,

244
00:13:45,829 --> 00:13:47,410
meaning that console players were left

245
00:13:47,450 --> 00:13:49,751
completely without the ability to remap.

246
00:13:50,512 --> 00:13:52,552
This was a highly requested feature and

247
00:13:52,653 --> 00:13:56,334
incredibly helpful for gamers with various impairments,

248
00:13:56,534 --> 00:13:58,775
or if they were using a specialty controller

249
00:13:58,795 --> 00:14:02,897
that did not work with our out-of-the-box control schemes.

250
00:14:02,917 --> 00:14:04,458
What was interesting for me personally

251
00:14:04,498 --> 00:14:05,758
while I was digging into this feature,

252
00:14:05,778 --> 00:14:07,359
I mean, kind of pushing it to get made,

253
00:14:07,399 --> 00:14:08,480
was I learned at one time.

254
00:14:09,437 --> 00:14:12,940
This feature had actually been in development, but it ended up being cut.

255
00:14:13,020 --> 00:14:18,204
Although there was a couple people who had championed it previously, they had kind of

256
00:14:18,264 --> 00:14:23,609
attempted to simply duplicate the system that was on PC onto console, and it led to a kind

257
00:14:23,669 --> 00:14:24,790
of buggy design.

258
00:14:24,810 --> 00:14:29,574
And the result was a system that really wasn't worth the effort, and so it got cut.

259
00:14:31,027 --> 00:14:34,228
Now, once we decided that, no, we're going back,

260
00:14:34,248 --> 00:14:36,409
we're going to do this right, is something we need to tackle,

261
00:14:36,969 --> 00:14:39,069
we actually took inspiration straight

262
00:14:39,089 --> 00:14:40,750
from a previous GDC talk of mine,

263
00:14:40,770 --> 00:14:44,651
which I'm sure you all saw, No More Excuses, Your Guide

264
00:14:44,711 --> 00:14:47,471
to Accessible Design, and we implemented the button swap

265
00:14:47,491 --> 00:14:47,851
method.

266
00:14:48,352 --> 00:14:50,012
Now, although I'm sure you all saw it,

267
00:14:50,812 --> 00:14:52,613
let me go ahead and refresh your memory on what that was.

268
00:14:53,773 --> 00:14:57,736
We offer the player different preset control schemes.

269
00:14:57,816 --> 00:15:01,579
Evolve actually shipped with five different control schemes for Hunters

270
00:15:01,719 --> 00:15:03,740
and four for Monsters that the player could choose from.

271
00:15:06,397 --> 00:15:11,679
The next part of this process is making sure the control schemes group different actions together.

272
00:15:11,899 --> 00:15:16,281
If you look at this one, you can see that Action Reload is grouped together on the left.

273
00:15:16,801 --> 00:15:19,662
Then on the right, Action Use Cover is grouped together.

274
00:15:19,942 --> 00:15:22,803
That is what I am talking about when grouping things together differently.

275
00:15:23,523 --> 00:15:26,725
This mixture of actions, not just rearranging the buttons,

276
00:15:27,645 --> 00:15:31,946
allows the player more customization when they are trying to remap their controls.

277
00:15:35,808 --> 00:15:37,709
Once a player decides on what control scheme they want,

278
00:15:38,050 --> 00:15:41,992
the player is simply given the option to switch what is mapped between two buttons.

279
00:15:42,192 --> 00:15:44,754
Everything that is with that button goes with it.

280
00:15:45,234 --> 00:15:51,438
It is not like, I want useCover to move with action but reload stays there.

281
00:15:51,458 --> 00:15:55,221
No, you would have to find another control scheme that offered that pairing.

282
00:15:56,282 --> 00:16:01,245
I know a lot of people get, like, Tara, my button Y does six things.

283
00:16:02,149 --> 00:16:05,412
just have everything that goes with Y move in this method.

284
00:16:07,114 --> 00:16:09,296
So for getting this in and getting this tested on Evolve,

285
00:16:09,997 --> 00:16:11,959
it was actually really easy.

286
00:16:12,019 --> 00:16:14,661
We avoided a lot of the pitfalls of remappable controls

287
00:16:15,162 --> 00:16:18,805
because we already had a remapping system on PC.

288
00:16:19,186 --> 00:16:21,989
So our UI was already set up to be able to update.

289
00:16:22,029 --> 00:16:25,832
We already had the UI elements for all of these icons

290
00:16:25,892 --> 00:16:26,653
already available.

291
00:16:28,208 --> 00:16:32,531
We had like one small thing where like a monster scheme and hunter scheme had

292
00:16:32,591 --> 00:16:35,973
something that was shared on controller but we just had to split that and that

293
00:16:35,993 --> 00:16:40,597
was pretty much all we had to do. The largest loss of work was the first time

294
00:16:40,757 --> 00:16:45,661
someone tried to do it and it actually got cut. Now so this is a system for us

295
00:16:45,781 --> 00:16:49,183
that had very little overhead in terms of getting it implemented.

296
00:16:49,921 --> 00:16:52,142
But as I was saying previously, if we didn't already

297
00:16:52,182 --> 00:16:55,083
have a PC remapping available and we didn't already

298
00:16:55,123 --> 00:16:57,824
have all that art ready with UI, this

299
00:16:57,844 --> 00:16:58,725
could have been something that would

300
00:16:58,745 --> 00:17:04,727
have been way more expensive to add in after the fact.

301
00:17:04,747 --> 00:17:07,989
So these two features were the first accessibility patch

302
00:17:08,009 --> 00:17:08,949
that we actually got launched.

303
00:17:12,147 --> 00:17:14,008
Sorry, excuse me.

304
00:17:14,128 --> 00:17:16,589
We decided that we were just going to roll out

305
00:17:16,609 --> 00:17:19,010
the accessibility features in chunks as they were ready,

306
00:17:19,170 --> 00:17:22,632
rather than waiting for the game to be 100 percent accessible,

307
00:17:22,652 --> 00:17:23,973
because that will never happen anyway.

308
00:17:25,794 --> 00:17:26,994
In our weekly livestream,

309
00:17:27,195 --> 00:17:30,036
we took time to educate our audience on, number one,

310
00:17:30,496 --> 00:17:32,217
the idea of what game accessibility is

311
00:17:32,958 --> 00:17:34,778
and why it was important.

312
00:17:35,039 --> 00:17:37,520
Not why just it was important to us as developers,

313
00:17:37,920 --> 00:17:38,901
but to us as gamers.

314
00:17:39,761 --> 00:17:45,570
and we showed off all the features and told players how they could provide additional feedback,

315
00:17:45,971 --> 00:17:50,457
requests, and we really opened the door for accessibility conversations with our players.

316
00:17:50,517 --> 00:17:52,761
We wanted it to be a dialogue.

317
00:17:53,713 --> 00:17:58,416
So the accessibility portion of our live stream lasted over 30 minutes of Evolve's weekly

318
00:17:58,476 --> 00:18:01,458
live stream on the Twitch channel, which has over 23,000 followers.

319
00:18:01,839 --> 00:18:03,900
And it was also hosted by the Turtle Rock Twitch channel.

320
00:18:04,720 --> 00:18:06,081
So I got to be on there.

321
00:18:06,121 --> 00:18:06,922
I was really excited.

322
00:18:06,942 --> 00:18:13,386
I didn't, you know, there aren't many live streams that highlight accessibility.

323
00:18:13,787 --> 00:18:15,888
So for me personally, it was a big day.

324
00:18:18,114 --> 00:18:21,976
But obviously, we didn't just stop at two separate features.

325
00:18:22,736 --> 00:18:24,377
Around this time, we were actually

326
00:18:24,417 --> 00:18:27,798
getting ready for the launch of Evolve Stage 2, which

327
00:18:27,858 --> 00:18:30,479
was the free-to-play relaunch of the game.

328
00:18:31,739 --> 00:18:35,401
And we wanted to make the game even more accessible.

329
00:18:37,985 --> 00:18:40,466
We ended up having a big update on our visual effects.

330
00:18:40,826 --> 00:18:44,769
One of the things that became very apparent was there was a lot,

331
00:18:44,849 --> 00:18:47,631
like a literal shit ton of things happening in our game.

332
00:18:48,511 --> 00:18:50,693
There were four different guns that could be fired,

333
00:18:50,973 --> 00:18:53,555
there were area attacks, monster attacks, there were wildlife,

334
00:18:54,135 --> 00:18:59,198
and some of it was very, very obtrusive and often happening simultaneously.

335
00:19:00,099 --> 00:19:05,141
To be honest, a lot of these visual effects were not only making it difficult for players

336
00:19:05,181 --> 00:19:08,103
with visual impairments, it was just hard for players in general.

337
00:19:08,123 --> 00:19:13,445
We took this approach at overhauling the visual effects and we updated almost half of them

338
00:19:13,766 --> 00:19:18,068
with the goal of clarity, less noise, and defined borders.

339
00:19:18,088 --> 00:19:23,611
If you look at this example, this is Hyde firing his flamethrower in a toxic grenade

340
00:19:23,651 --> 00:19:23,931
cloud.

341
00:19:25,033 --> 00:19:27,820
And the before and after is drastic.

342
00:19:27,900 --> 00:19:31,408
In the left, like, you don't even know what he's firing at.

343
00:19:31,829 --> 00:19:34,234
So obviously, like, these were big changes.

344
00:19:36,762 --> 00:19:38,864
These changes were across the board.

345
00:19:38,884 --> 00:19:44,769
If you look at this screenshot, you can see the before and after of Kratkin's Aftershock.

346
00:19:45,030 --> 00:19:46,992
Before, it was a completely fuzzy vortex.

347
00:19:47,352 --> 00:19:52,817
But after the redesign, it had a well-defined and high contrast edge that allowed players

348
00:19:52,877 --> 00:19:55,060
to know where the end of this was.

349
00:19:55,240 --> 00:19:57,102
What was the hit zone.

350
00:19:58,240 --> 00:20:02,162
This actually helped to relieve a major problem that we had been experiencing.

351
00:20:03,043 --> 00:20:06,304
Only players who played against Kraken all the time, who were really experienced,

352
00:20:06,785 --> 00:20:10,026
knew how far you had to dodge to avoid getting hit.

353
00:20:10,426 --> 00:20:14,288
You just had to know before these changes went in.

354
00:20:14,408 --> 00:20:17,930
Now that I had a defined border and a clear outline,

355
00:20:17,950 --> 00:20:21,672
it was easy to see all players, even new players,

356
00:20:22,012 --> 00:20:23,973
knew where they needed to go to get out of the way.

357
00:20:26,070 --> 00:20:31,012
As I mentioned previously, we often had multiple complex visual effects happening simultaneously.

358
00:20:32,073 --> 00:20:34,074
Sometimes they would stack and stick.

359
00:20:34,094 --> 00:20:40,617
Another thing we did to help this was develop a unified language for all of our visual effects

360
00:20:40,677 --> 00:20:44,559
to make them similar so you had a better idea of what was happening, where it was going

361
00:20:44,579 --> 00:20:47,120
to happen, so we didn't have too much happening in one place.

362
00:20:48,180 --> 00:20:53,303
Much like with the concept art in dealing with colorblindness, we had a very similar

363
00:20:53,323 --> 00:20:54,843
approach on making sure we weren't.

364
00:20:55,524 --> 00:20:58,304
doing things that were going to be too busy or might cause new conflicts

365
00:20:59,805 --> 00:21:01,285
become a problem going forward.

366
00:21:04,066 --> 00:21:05,507
One thing that also became clear to us

367
00:21:05,947 --> 00:21:10,368
was although our tutorials allowed for a safe space for the player to learn

368
00:21:10,728 --> 00:21:14,049
the controls without dying, it wasn't a good representation

369
00:21:14,489 --> 00:21:17,690
of seeing if the player actually understood the game, the cues around them,

370
00:21:18,111 --> 00:21:19,131
or even just how to play.

371
00:21:21,899 --> 00:21:25,782
Originally, we only offered Goliath and Markov tutorials.

372
00:21:25,822 --> 00:21:28,244
Later, we expanded them to include these Hunt tutorials,

373
00:21:28,805 --> 00:21:30,887
which were basically advanced tutorials.

374
00:21:32,308 --> 00:21:35,571
Each one catered to a specific character in that class,

375
00:21:35,631 --> 00:21:38,334
who we determined was sort of the best starter character

376
00:21:38,354 --> 00:21:40,676
for that group, the one that was normally the easiest to use.

377
00:21:41,296 --> 00:21:43,158
And these tutorials allowed for everyone

378
00:21:43,218 --> 00:21:45,559
to get a better grasp of the basics before moving on.

379
00:21:46,120 --> 00:21:48,802
And it was a space that the player could take their time

380
00:21:49,162 --> 00:21:51,184
and adjust to any class without pressure

381
00:21:51,324 --> 00:21:52,305
and helpful guidance.

382
00:21:52,765 --> 00:21:54,106
So in our original tutorials,

383
00:21:54,126 --> 00:21:56,968
let's say we had a gamer with a specialty controller

384
00:21:57,308 --> 00:21:59,590
who was trying to see if they could, you know,

385
00:21:59,810 --> 00:22:01,151
use their controller to play.

386
00:22:02,245 --> 00:22:07,107
They couldn't learn that from our original tutorials because it wasn't really playing.

387
00:22:07,267 --> 00:22:11,369
It was, you are here, press A to jetpack there.

388
00:22:11,850 --> 00:22:13,190
Not a very good representation.

389
00:22:13,551 --> 00:22:18,493
So with these advanced tutorials, it was much better for someone trying to understand if

390
00:22:18,513 --> 00:22:19,854
they could play or trying to learn to play.

391
00:22:21,254 --> 00:22:24,777
These tutorials were actually one of the most complex things we ended up retrofitting.

392
00:22:26,017 --> 00:22:29,020
It was a great experience for us as devs, though.

393
00:22:29,460 --> 00:22:32,462
Not only, number one, did we have to see if we actually understood how to play our game,

394
00:22:33,223 --> 00:22:35,985
we had to teach how to play it to others.

395
00:22:37,106 --> 00:22:41,829
We ended up actually having to develop a new audio queuing system to ensure the most important

396
00:22:41,849 --> 00:22:46,013
VO, which was the voiceover from Abe and Kyra, who were leading you through this tutorial.

397
00:22:47,053 --> 00:22:49,274
make sure they were heard above other noises.

398
00:22:49,694 --> 00:22:53,136
We also had to develop a priority system for the subtitles

399
00:22:53,276 --> 00:22:56,557
because we also didn't want them to get stomped out

400
00:22:56,577 --> 00:22:58,338
by less important systemic lines.

401
00:22:58,398 --> 00:23:00,439
Like if Kyra was telling you something important

402
00:23:00,459 --> 00:23:01,699
about how to fight this monster,

403
00:23:02,199 --> 00:23:04,020
we didn't want Hank saying reloading

404
00:23:04,400 --> 00:23:05,781
to push her subtitle off screen.

405
00:23:06,868 --> 00:23:12,150
So, and this also was, you know, heavily scripted and just required a lot of man work to get

406
00:23:12,170 --> 00:23:12,430
done.

407
00:23:12,571 --> 00:23:17,432
So, this was something that doing it after the fact and trying to teach players, you

408
00:23:17,452 --> 00:23:20,433
know, how to do this afterwards was pretty high.

409
00:23:23,946 --> 00:23:28,808
Another one of our largest efforts was actually updating our in-game UI and having it match

410
00:23:29,109 --> 00:23:31,790
the existing visual effects.

411
00:23:31,830 --> 00:23:33,290
There could be a disparity.

412
00:23:33,310 --> 00:23:39,253
A UI element could be a blue bar on a health thing, but a green cross in the world.

413
00:23:39,313 --> 00:23:42,314
You may not realize that was telling you the same information twice.

414
00:23:43,557 --> 00:23:47,878
And we also found out that we had a ton of in-game occurrences that were either sound-based

415
00:23:48,618 --> 00:23:53,540
and sometimes so subtle that players, even without hearing impairments, just didn't know

416
00:23:53,580 --> 00:23:59,822
that they existed, or the UI was so subtle or lacking contrast that they were overlooked

417
00:23:59,882 --> 00:24:01,002
and frequently just unused.

418
00:24:01,442 --> 00:24:05,943
So we took efforts to double down on communicating a lot of this information, and this included

419
00:24:06,464 --> 00:24:10,145
being poisoned, healing. The Defense Matrix is shown here.

420
00:24:11,025 --> 00:24:17,448
Previously, if someone was being shielded, they would have a little bar on top of their health bar.

421
00:24:17,848 --> 00:24:21,690
But here, as you can see, the visual effects, boom, it is right on top of the character.

422
00:24:21,710 --> 00:24:26,692
It is a lot easier to see. Also, if you had a Defense Matrix on you,

423
00:24:26,712 --> 00:24:31,574
I should have got a better screenshot now that I think of it, but on the left you can see you

424
00:24:31,654 --> 00:24:34,155
have that same icon showing up for you.

425
00:24:35,516 --> 00:24:39,486
It looks the same, the visuals are the same, they're bolder, they're a lot easier to see.

426
00:24:41,292 --> 00:24:43,213
We also did this for shielding fire damage.

427
00:24:43,974 --> 00:24:49,197
Beyond this, we also took steps to make a lot of other things visually clear.

428
00:24:49,778 --> 00:24:55,021
Visual tells dead carcasses, so if a monster killed a wildlife and went on its way,

429
00:24:55,041 --> 00:24:59,064
that carcass would be there to let you know that the monster had gone this way.

430
00:24:59,444 --> 00:25:02,546
But if you couldn't notice the carcass, obviously that's not helpful.

431
00:25:02,907 --> 00:25:06,049
We ended up putting outlines on them so you could see them more clearly.

432
00:25:06,669 --> 00:25:09,151
We also did the same thing for elite wildlife.

433
00:25:09,171 --> 00:25:09,851
If they had like a...

434
00:25:10,532 --> 00:25:13,733
tower of light. They offered you buffs if you kill them, so you want to kill them,

435
00:25:14,193 --> 00:25:16,254
but if you can't find them, it doesn't do you any good.

436
00:25:17,514 --> 00:25:24,196
We also added new UI for major gameplay events, such as teammates dying, being revived, that kind of thing.

437
00:25:25,465 --> 00:25:29,125
Of course, you cannot add UI elements for everything.

438
00:25:29,786 --> 00:25:30,546
That would be terrible.

439
00:25:31,886 --> 00:25:34,187
We also decided to put an in-game announcer

440
00:25:35,067 --> 00:25:37,647
who was capturing a lot of these events.

441
00:25:37,787 --> 00:25:40,688
If something was there visually, but maybe not strong,

442
00:25:40,708 --> 00:25:43,188
or it was not something we thought should have a UI element,

443
00:25:43,989 --> 00:25:47,029
the VO of the announcer could help reinforce that

444
00:25:47,469 --> 00:25:49,170
and display that information in a second way.

445
00:25:51,581 --> 00:25:53,221
Like I said, we just kind of went crazy.

446
00:25:53,261 --> 00:25:55,522
We got all sorts of new UI things.

447
00:25:56,022 --> 00:25:58,143
We had the ping that changed, and now all of a sudden,

448
00:25:58,563 --> 00:26:01,483
if you are harpooned, you get an icon for that.

449
00:26:01,544 --> 00:26:03,264
Stuff that, again, we had a lot of things

450
00:26:03,304 --> 00:26:06,245
that we just kind of expected players to figure out.

451
00:26:06,645 --> 00:26:09,526
At one point, we updated how Behemoth's armor worked,

452
00:26:10,086 --> 00:26:12,186
and no one knew what was happening.

453
00:26:12,246 --> 00:26:13,867
We ended up adding information for that.

454
00:26:13,887 --> 00:26:15,647
We are telling you when your dropship is coming.

455
00:26:16,847 --> 00:26:19,148
Really, there was a lot of information we realized

456
00:26:19,608 --> 00:26:20,808
that if you just didn't know it.

457
00:26:21,229 --> 00:26:25,452
then you are not going to get it from in-game anywhere.

458
00:26:25,952 --> 00:26:30,176
That was a lot of what we were doing.

459
00:26:30,596 --> 00:26:31,737
One of the other things we realized,

460
00:26:31,777 --> 00:26:33,818
and I think that goes in tandem,

461
00:26:33,939 --> 00:26:35,680
is that Evolve had a difficulty problem.

462
00:26:36,200 --> 00:26:38,562
We found that our gameplay was frequently inaccessible.

463
00:26:40,348 --> 00:26:43,590
You know, if one player were underperforming, as it were,

464
00:26:43,610 --> 00:26:46,732
it could ruin the experience for the entire team

465
00:26:47,492 --> 00:26:49,574
and put them in a situation where they couldn't recover.

466
00:26:49,594 --> 00:26:53,096
It was creating this extraordinarily toxic

467
00:26:53,636 --> 00:26:55,998
get good kind of community,

468
00:26:56,058 --> 00:26:57,859
which obviously wasn't what we wanted.

469
00:26:59,106 --> 00:27:05,819
So one of the things we did was change our gameplay to more evenly distribute these gameplay tasks.

470
00:27:06,100 --> 00:27:10,569
Make it so that more people could take a chance at doing some of this stuff.

471
00:27:11,876 --> 00:27:17,259
It meant that if there was a struggle for a certain player with a particular class,

472
00:27:17,719 --> 00:27:20,580
the team could balance it out and still have a chance at winning.

473
00:27:20,981 --> 00:27:24,983
We wanted to create gameplay that was inclusive, where a whole team could work together

474
00:27:25,483 --> 00:27:28,444
rather than punish new or inexperienced players,

475
00:27:28,924 --> 00:27:32,006
or a player who was struggling because they weren't good at a particular class.

476
00:27:32,606 --> 00:27:34,247
We ended up changing a lot.

477
00:27:35,288 --> 00:27:40,450
We reworked three of the major class abilities, which are kind of like, you know...

478
00:27:41,190 --> 00:27:46,992
staples in the game. For me, the best example of this is the mobile arena, or

479
00:27:47,333 --> 00:27:51,834
as players just called it, the dome. It originally could only be thrown by the

480
00:27:51,914 --> 00:27:55,956
trapper, and the trapper would have to throw it to where they thought the

481
00:27:55,976 --> 00:27:56,916
monster was going to be.

482
00:27:59,135 --> 00:28:03,798
For some players, such as myself, being a trapper was legitimately stressful.

483
00:28:04,458 --> 00:28:08,401
I personally lacked both the skill and reflexes to capture the monster.

484
00:28:09,162 --> 00:28:12,564
I was known for throwing domes and catching absolutely nothing in them.

485
00:28:13,264 --> 00:28:16,046
It had a significant recharge time, so once I threw that dome,

486
00:28:16,426 --> 00:28:20,869
missed the monster, we'd all have to hang out for another two minutes until I get to try again,

487
00:28:20,889 --> 00:28:23,851
at which point I'd probably still miss the monster.

488
00:28:25,089 --> 00:28:29,292
We changed it for stage two so that all classes could throw the dome.

489
00:28:29,792 --> 00:28:34,576
Even better, when you went to throw the dome, it came down automatically over the monster.

490
00:28:35,116 --> 00:28:39,259
Now anyone could throw it, and you were guaranteed to capture the monster.

491
00:28:39,359 --> 00:28:43,582
We had to make some changes to how the dome worked once you captured the monster because of that,

492
00:28:44,083 --> 00:28:46,264
but it was still so much better.

493
00:28:46,925 --> 00:28:50,828
For myself and a lot of other people, the class went from something we literally dreaded

494
00:28:50,848 --> 00:28:53,710
to something that was new and exciting to explore.

495
00:28:55,648 --> 00:28:58,150
Some of the characters even got more than one class change.

496
00:28:58,230 --> 00:29:02,293
With Behemoth, we actually took time to not only redo his abilities,

497
00:29:02,994 --> 00:29:04,735
we fixed tons of long-standing bugs.

498
00:29:04,775 --> 00:29:06,716
He basically got a full refactor.

499
00:29:08,157 --> 00:29:11,960
But we did some other stuff, like tinkering with how our Aim Assist worked,

500
00:29:12,260 --> 00:29:15,643
changing our controls on our...

501
00:29:16,871 --> 00:29:19,992
What's the right word? The sensitivities on our controller to make it better.

502
00:29:20,092 --> 00:29:22,133
I mean, we just went ham.

503
00:29:22,773 --> 00:29:27,235
I've never worked on another project that basically took so many core tenets of gameplay

504
00:29:27,255 --> 00:29:29,036
and we're like, fuck it, doing it live.

505
00:29:29,056 --> 00:29:32,417
Again, patching every week. We're crazy people.

506
00:29:33,978 --> 00:29:36,138
But it was all better, and it made a lot of improvements.

507
00:29:38,959 --> 00:29:40,721
Now, as I mentioned earlier, in many cases,

508
00:29:40,861 --> 00:29:44,125
gamers with disabilities don't know if they can play a game

509
00:29:44,305 --> 00:29:47,629
until after they buy it, at which point,

510
00:29:47,829 --> 00:29:48,910
they'll find out it doesn't work.

511
00:29:49,330 --> 00:29:51,513
And that's why it was so important for us

512
00:29:51,553 --> 00:29:54,095
to publish that list of game accessibility

513
00:29:54,135 --> 00:29:54,976
features that we had.

514
00:29:55,617 --> 00:29:57,759
But in-game, after we went free to play,

515
00:29:57,799 --> 00:29:58,941
we had a similar problem.

516
00:29:59,021 --> 00:29:59,842
So now,

517
00:30:00,662 --> 00:30:02,783
Anyone could download the game, anyone could play for free,

518
00:30:03,383 --> 00:30:07,864
but you could still spend either real money or in-game currency

519
00:30:07,884 --> 00:30:10,305
to unlock new characters, unlock new perks.

520
00:30:11,045 --> 00:30:15,067
And again, we really had no way for any particular player

521
00:30:15,087 --> 00:30:17,607
to know if they liked that character

522
00:30:17,627 --> 00:30:20,108
or if they could even use that character or that perk

523
00:30:20,728 --> 00:30:22,629
without that initial investment.

524
00:30:24,460 --> 00:30:27,102
Again, we wanted to give the players this information.

525
00:30:27,583 --> 00:30:30,605
For us, we figured the best way to do this was to remove the problem

526
00:30:31,005 --> 00:30:35,868
by implementing a try-before-you-buy system for all characters and perks.

527
00:30:35,908 --> 00:30:39,451
The player is actually able to go into single player and play anything,

528
00:30:40,171 --> 00:30:42,613
any of the characters, any of the perks, as much as they wanted,

529
00:30:43,053 --> 00:30:44,394
for no cost to them.

530
00:30:44,834 --> 00:30:48,077
They could go in and see if they liked it before they spent their money.

531
00:30:48,397 --> 00:30:51,259
Obviously, playing in single player isn't quite the same.

532
00:30:52,019 --> 00:30:53,180
as playing in multiplayer.

533
00:30:53,681 --> 00:30:56,783
We also offer free characters on rotation every week

534
00:30:57,143 --> 00:30:59,625
so that players could try these new characters

535
00:31:00,146 --> 00:31:03,488
that they didn't own in multiplayer as well as single player.

536
00:31:07,446 --> 00:31:11,690
Something else that was really fun was for Global Accessibility Awareness Day,

537
00:31:11,750 --> 00:31:12,731
which is in May every year,

538
00:31:14,112 --> 00:31:17,435
we saw Uncharted 4's awesome video

539
00:31:17,855 --> 00:31:20,017
that they released about their game accessibility features

540
00:31:20,537 --> 00:31:22,879
as part of Global Accessibility Awareness Day.

541
00:31:22,899 --> 00:31:25,802
Basically, I got super jealous because I was like,

542
00:31:25,842 --> 00:31:28,204
we've done accessibility work, this isn't fair.

543
00:31:28,284 --> 00:31:31,066
Why does Naughty Dog get an awesome video?

544
00:31:31,086 --> 00:31:33,488
So I was like, we should do something.

545
00:31:33,528 --> 00:31:34,589
We should do something right now.

546
00:31:35,913 --> 00:31:41,836
So literally right right then we're like, well, what we can do we can do a stream and so we

547
00:31:42,397 --> 00:31:44,958
Didn't even like go to our we have a

548
00:31:45,418 --> 00:31:49,101
Like a streaming area with like a proper green screen and all that stuff. We didn't even do that

549
00:31:49,381 --> 00:31:54,103
We like rocked a whiteboard up behind my desk and erased it put a camera on my desk

550
00:31:54,123 --> 00:31:55,924
We're like we're doing it here. We're doing it right now

551
00:31:57,917 --> 00:32:02,563
So yeah, we just did a global accessibility awareness day stream about Evolve just straight from my desk in the office.

552
00:32:04,025 --> 00:32:08,290
So on the stream we talked about some of the changes that were due to be released in our next big update,

553
00:32:08,630 --> 00:32:11,293
which were some of the things that I've kind of talked about up to this point.

554
00:32:12,335 --> 00:32:12,615
And

555
00:32:13,796 --> 00:32:15,298
we talked about some other changes.

556
00:32:15,999 --> 00:32:18,600
that were going to be coming up as well.

557
00:32:19,340 --> 00:32:21,641
And what was really great was the amount of people

558
00:32:21,661 --> 00:32:23,482
who showed up to the stream,

559
00:32:23,582 --> 00:32:26,663
and very few of them are actually gamers with impairments.

560
00:32:26,683 --> 00:32:28,484
They were just gamers who were excited to learn.

561
00:32:29,830 --> 00:32:32,011
The stream was also a great opportunity for us.

562
00:32:32,631 --> 00:32:36,993
Our, again, low-budget, at-my-desk stream with a whiteboard as the background got picked

563
00:32:37,053 --> 00:32:40,615
up by a few blogs who were rounding up the news for the day, for Global Accessibility

564
00:32:40,635 --> 00:32:41,175
Awareness Day.

565
00:32:41,195 --> 00:32:45,557
And so we got exposure through accessibility that we wouldn't have otherwise gotten.

566
00:32:46,297 --> 00:32:50,839
And we also announced two other features that, at the time, didn't have a cemented ship date

567
00:32:51,320 --> 00:32:52,440
that were still in the works.

568
00:32:54,754 --> 00:32:56,916
Now, one of these features were closed captions.

569
00:32:58,058 --> 00:33:03,003
This was a feature we actually started developing way back at the same time as remappable controls

570
00:33:03,124 --> 00:33:06,548
and colorblind mode, but it didn't get done in time for the first patch.

571
00:33:08,991 --> 00:33:15,356
Although hooking up the system to give the options of subtitles and closed captions was done really quickly without many issues,

572
00:33:15,956 --> 00:33:20,821
the major stumbling block was actually what sounds should be triggering a cue.

573
00:33:20,841 --> 00:33:24,644
You know, what sounds do we have in game that are actually really important to gameplay?

574
00:33:26,637 --> 00:33:29,118
So along with the engineer who built the system,

575
00:33:29,939 --> 00:33:32,241
I took a stab at making a first draft of lists of

576
00:33:32,861 --> 00:33:36,564
what sounds I thought were important and should be triggered with the system.

577
00:33:37,244 --> 00:33:40,106
So once I had the list, I brought it over to our balance group.

578
00:33:40,387 --> 00:33:43,549
So our balance group was comprised mostly of QA

579
00:33:43,949 --> 00:33:47,011
that we had hired out of the competitive community that

580
00:33:47,392 --> 00:33:50,794
would make sure that when we made changes we weren't breaking our game at

581
00:33:50,914 --> 00:33:51,755
a super high level.

582
00:33:52,976 --> 00:33:57,259
They knew how to properly utilize every cue in game, so I brought it to them.

583
00:33:58,160 --> 00:34:02,263
Here is an accurate rendition of how our conversation went.

584
00:34:02,804 --> 00:34:07,067
Hey guys, look, I have this list of awesome game accessibility things that should trigger

585
00:34:07,087 --> 00:34:07,367
sound.

586
00:34:07,687 --> 00:34:08,648
Can you give it a once over?

587
00:34:08,668 --> 00:34:09,529
I am sure it is perfect.

588
00:34:11,450 --> 00:34:13,432
Tara, you left spotters off the list.

589
00:34:15,093 --> 00:34:16,474
I have no idea what you are talking about.

590
00:34:18,155 --> 00:34:20,938
Tara, don't you know spotters make a noise when they hear the monster?

591
00:34:22,932 --> 00:34:24,454
No, I didn't know that.

592
00:34:26,696 --> 00:34:30,781
So, although I will admit I don't have the best hearing,

593
00:34:31,522 --> 00:34:33,445
I had no idea that that sound was even in-game.

594
00:34:34,025 --> 00:34:37,970
And that was just one of the many sounds I learned in-game

595
00:34:38,230 --> 00:34:41,134
that meant something that I had no clue about.

596
00:34:42,495 --> 00:34:45,336
This coupled with UI changes I mentioned earlier,

597
00:34:45,356 --> 00:34:48,337
were just another way we had information

598
00:34:48,457 --> 00:34:50,818
that was not getting to not just our core players,

599
00:34:52,059 --> 00:34:53,900
but especially those who had impairments.

600
00:34:54,960 --> 00:34:56,621
What ended up happening with this was,

601
00:34:56,641 --> 00:34:59,862
at the same time we were trying to identify the sounds,

602
00:35:00,362 --> 00:35:01,623
we had started making a lot of

603
00:35:01,663 --> 00:35:03,964
these crazy gameplay adjustments.

604
00:35:05,247 --> 00:35:10,109
We ended up holding off until after the adjustments were made and seeing what new UI we were adding

605
00:35:10,149 --> 00:35:15,271
before we went to put sounds on the closed caption system, so we could wrap our head

606
00:35:15,291 --> 00:35:18,172
around what wasn't being reinforced in some way.

607
00:35:18,952 --> 00:35:21,173
Unfortunately, this was a feature that never shipped.

608
00:35:21,273 --> 00:35:26,995
It was still in progress when Turtle Rock's contract ended with 2K for Evolve.

609
00:35:27,575 --> 00:35:31,596
It was something that I was personally really excited about, so I was pretty bummed when

610
00:35:31,636 --> 00:35:32,197
it didn't get out.

611
00:35:35,833 --> 00:35:37,814
The other one was the comm wheel.

612
00:35:38,694 --> 00:35:42,095
One of the things that had become very apparent

613
00:35:42,576 --> 00:35:45,457
was if you weren't using a mic or couldn't use a mic,

614
00:35:46,257 --> 00:35:49,018
our game was nearly impossible to play.

615
00:35:49,498 --> 00:35:52,619
Communicating with your teammates and other players was key.

616
00:35:53,179 --> 00:35:56,041
So sure, on PC, you had in-game text chat,

617
00:35:56,461 --> 00:35:58,561
but number one, that wasn't always fast enough.

618
00:35:58,942 --> 00:36:01,382
If you're in the middle of a fight,

619
00:36:01,443 --> 00:36:03,283
like hitting enter type stuff,

620
00:36:04,144 --> 00:36:06,104
not very efficient.

621
00:36:06,424 --> 00:36:09,685
There wasn't actually any way to do that on console at all.

622
00:36:09,785 --> 00:36:12,926
If you are on console, there was no way for you to talk to your other players

623
00:36:13,406 --> 00:36:14,087
if you didn't have a mic.

624
00:36:15,447 --> 00:36:16,807
We started developing a Commwheel.

625
00:36:18,028 --> 00:36:20,188
This is the original concept art.

626
00:36:20,308 --> 00:36:24,490
Unfortunately, I wasn't able to get an in-game screenshot of

627
00:36:25,150 --> 00:36:27,611
what it ended up looking like.

628
00:36:27,631 --> 00:36:28,631
It was fairly true to this.

629
00:36:28,691 --> 00:36:29,671
Basically, our goal was

630
00:36:30,949 --> 00:36:34,412
Identify the most important things you need to tell your teammates.

631
00:36:35,252 --> 00:36:42,217
I am down, we should group up, that kind of stuff, like heal me, blah, blah, blah.

632
00:36:43,078 --> 00:36:47,501
Once you triggered it, it would have some sort of in-game visual effects.

633
00:36:47,541 --> 00:36:51,103
For example, if you wanted to group up here,

634
00:36:52,164 --> 00:36:53,645
a little visual effect popped up in the world

635
00:36:54,065 --> 00:36:55,266
to show you where you wanted to group up.

636
00:36:57,418 --> 00:37:03,943
Honestly, the largest problem we encountered was trying to have a comm wheel that nicely

637
00:37:03,983 --> 00:37:06,805
integrated with both platforms in terms of controlling it.

638
00:37:08,947 --> 00:37:14,110
Since we'd used so much real estate on the controller, particularly already, for everything

639
00:37:14,130 --> 00:37:14,571
that you could do.

640
00:37:15,547 --> 00:37:18,529
And we had play tested it.

641
00:37:19,069 --> 00:37:21,391
We're still kind of tweaking it to make it

642
00:37:21,831 --> 00:37:23,612
a truly great usable experience.

643
00:37:24,072 --> 00:37:26,494
And also around that time was when our contract ended

644
00:37:26,614 --> 00:37:27,274
with Evolve.

645
00:37:27,314 --> 00:37:29,136
So this was another thing that was in progress that

646
00:37:29,156 --> 00:37:32,118
didn't get to ship, but we were pretty excited about it.

647
00:37:34,579 --> 00:37:38,722
So what should you learn about Total Rock and Evolve's

648
00:37:39,322 --> 00:37:40,923
adventure and accessibility retrofitting?

649
00:37:41,986 --> 00:37:45,889
So some of the things we implemented weren't that much work to add them in after the fact,

650
00:37:46,209 --> 00:37:49,752
but some things that should have been stupid simple, like colorblind mode,

651
00:37:50,232 --> 00:37:51,853
ended up being huge endeavors.

652
00:37:52,534 --> 00:37:57,638
But none of the stuff would have been that difficult or hard if we had just thought about it early in development.

653
00:37:58,298 --> 00:38:00,820
If one person had mentioned it or kept track of it,

654
00:38:01,341 --> 00:38:03,642
maybe we wouldn't have made so many mistakes to begin with.

655
00:38:04,143 --> 00:38:08,886
So I know this doesn't sound like an actual lesson, but apparently it is worth repeating.

656
00:38:09,487 --> 00:38:12,649
Pre-production is the time to think about accessibility.

657
00:38:12,829 --> 00:38:15,751
Doing accessibility from the beginning is not expensive.

658
00:38:16,271 --> 00:38:18,973
Retrofitting accessibility can be incredibly costly.

659
00:38:19,293 --> 00:38:20,034
Please don't do it.

660
00:38:21,755 --> 00:38:24,296
The other thing we learned is, you know your game.

661
00:38:24,977 --> 00:38:26,018
You know how your game works.

662
00:38:26,498 --> 00:38:29,140
But to really understand how players engage your game,

663
00:38:29,540 --> 00:38:31,041
you need playtests with people who

664
00:38:31,081 --> 00:38:32,202
do not work on your project.

665
00:38:32,702 --> 00:38:35,364
At minimum, they should be on a different project, friends

666
00:38:35,404 --> 00:38:35,804
or family.

667
00:38:36,698 --> 00:38:40,490
people from outside your studio who don't know your game like you do.

668
00:38:41,524 --> 00:38:44,505
get some user research up in there, up in that business.

669
00:38:45,045 --> 00:38:46,785
So we knew how to play our game,

670
00:38:47,385 --> 00:38:49,706
but we needed to see if other people did.

671
00:38:49,726 --> 00:38:53,527
One of the things that I was also really jealous of,

672
00:38:53,547 --> 00:38:55,747
I mean, this talk should be subtitled

673
00:38:55,787 --> 00:38:57,008
Tara Jealous of Naughty Dog.

674
00:38:58,908 --> 00:39:00,248
We didn't have the resources to do it,

675
00:39:00,288 --> 00:39:02,049
but one of the things that Naughty Dog did

676
00:39:02,109 --> 00:39:04,629
when they were putting in their game accessibility features

677
00:39:04,970 --> 00:39:06,690
was they actually had gamers

678
00:39:07,210 --> 00:39:10,251
with different physical impairments come in and test it.

679
00:39:11,071 --> 00:39:14,117
that was something that I would have loved for us to have the time and

680
00:39:14,157 --> 00:39:15,039
resources to do.

681
00:39:15,480 --> 00:39:17,704
So if you get that chance, do it.

682
00:39:19,546 --> 00:39:23,830
Another thing was a lot of the changes that were massively beneficial to gamers with disabilities

683
00:39:24,391 --> 00:39:27,193
weren't always even proposed for accessibility reasons.

684
00:39:27,553 --> 00:39:33,559
They just happened to have a huge impact for these gamers while improving the experience of the core audience.

685
00:39:34,359 --> 00:39:37,803
Most accessibility features fell into this category.

686
00:39:38,203 --> 00:39:43,427
We didn't implement a single accessibility feature that hurt the core audience.

687
00:39:44,630 --> 00:39:47,032
And that's something that I have to fight all the time.

688
00:39:47,092 --> 00:39:49,553
I get told, oh, but no one will use this.

689
00:39:49,653 --> 00:39:52,374
This only, the core gamers won't like it.

690
00:39:53,195 --> 00:39:54,736
That's just absolutely not true.

691
00:39:55,156 --> 00:39:57,297
So don't think that that's bad.

692
00:39:58,778 --> 00:40:01,459
And lastly, our accessibility efforts

693
00:40:01,959 --> 00:40:03,900
wouldn't have been nearly as successful

694
00:40:04,401 --> 00:40:06,442
if we hadn't told people about them

695
00:40:06,602 --> 00:40:08,483
and got buy-in from our community.

696
00:40:09,463 --> 00:40:13,769
So we shared this information on our live streams, our forum, our social media accounts,

697
00:40:14,150 --> 00:40:19,357
and we created a dialogue with our players and we created an avenue to get feedback from them.

698
00:40:19,998 --> 00:40:23,082
We became more connected with our player base.

699
00:40:24,205 --> 00:40:26,806
And really the coolest thing about this was

700
00:40:28,547 --> 00:40:31,588
we created our own little army of accessibility advocates

701
00:40:31,649 --> 00:40:32,349
out of our players.

702
00:40:33,009 --> 00:40:34,470
So users in our forum,

703
00:40:34,590 --> 00:40:37,391
they were helping other players find what they need.

704
00:40:38,111 --> 00:40:40,152
The forum members were tagging devs and being like,

705
00:40:40,432 --> 00:40:42,493
hey, did you see so-and-so's request?

706
00:40:42,533 --> 00:40:44,114
I think this falls under accessibility.

707
00:40:44,654 --> 00:40:47,015
Or in some cases, they would want a feature and ask us,

708
00:40:47,355 --> 00:40:48,616
hey, I was interested in this.

709
00:40:48,976 --> 00:40:50,977
Would this also help someone with an impairment?

710
00:40:51,617 --> 00:40:52,537
And that's awesome.

711
00:40:52,917 --> 00:40:53,198
They were...

712
00:40:53,958 --> 00:40:58,659
getting empathy for these other gamers. I mean even today they still

713
00:40:59,580 --> 00:41:06,502
tweet at me cool accessibility stories or if they see it in the news and they share it with me and they're excited about

714
00:41:07,222 --> 00:41:09,743
helping more gamers game and

715
00:41:09,903 --> 00:41:15,725
like I actually have something to to back this up. So one of the coolest things that happened was Shara

716
00:41:16,365 --> 00:41:20,667
which is Shane and Tara, really official,

717
00:41:21,647 --> 00:41:23,828
